    <div class="overlay">
      <p>Sound familiar? Most men have tried 3–5 of these. All with the same result.</p>
      <span>The problem isn't the products. It's where they stop working.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>Let me walk you through every solution men try for dark circles — and explain exactly, scientifically, why each one cannot solve the problem.</p>

  <!-- DEMOLITION LIST -->
  <div class="s2-demolish">

    <div class="s2-demolish-item">
      <div class="s2-demolish-left">
        <span class="s2-demolish-x">✕</span>
        <span class="s2-demolish-icon">🧴</span>
      </div>
      <div class="s2-demolish-right">
        <strong>Eye Creams & Serums (CeraVe, The Ordinary, La Roche-Posay…)</strong>
        <p>Their active molecules — caffeine, vitamin C, peptides — are molecularly too large to cross the skin's surface barrier. They sit on the epidermis, provide temporary hydration, then evaporate. A study in the Journal of Controlled Release confirmed that topical caffeine penetrates less than 0.1mm into skin. Dark circles start at 0.3mm. The math simply doesn't work.</p>
        <span class="reason">Stopped at 0.1mm — needs 0.3mm+</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="s2-demolish-item">
      <div class="s2-demolish-left">
        <span class="s2-demolish-x">✕</span>
        <span class="s2-demolish-icon">🧊</span>
      </div>
      <div class="s2-demolish-right">
        <strong>Cold Spoons, Ice Rollers & Cooling Tools</strong>
        <p>These temporarily constrict blood vessels and reduce puffiness for 15–30 minutes. The moment you stop, blood flow returns and the swelling is back. It's not treatment — it's temporary masking. Like putting a finger in a leaking pipe. Every morning, same routine. Same result 20 minutes later.</p>
        <span class="reason">Temporary fix — effect lasts 15-30 min only</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="s2-demolish-item">
      <div class="s2-demolish-left">
        <span class="s2-demolish-x">✕</span>
        <span class="s2-demolish-icon">💊</span>
      </div>
      <div class="s2-demolish-right">
        <strong>Retinol Eye Creams</strong>
        <p>Retinol can mildly stimulate collagen over 6–12 months of daily use. But the under-eye skin is the most sensitive on your body — most men who try retinol under the eye end up with redness, peeling or irritation that makes circles look worse. Even best-case results take almost a year of daily compliance.</p>
        <span class="reason">6-12 months for mild results — often causes irritation</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="s2-demolish-item">
      <div class="s2-demolish-left">
        <span class="s2-demolish-x">✕</span>
        <span class="s2-demolish-icon">💧</span>
      </div>
      <div class="s2-demolish-right">
        <strong>Regular Hydrogel Eye Patches</strong>
        <p>These feel premium and look impressive. But they use the same passive delivery as creams. The patch sits on top of your skin, releases ingredients onto the surface, and dissolves before anything reaches the dermis. You're paying $3–5 per use for what is essentially a moisturizing mask that sits on the wrong layer.</p>
        <span class="reason">Same problem as creams — wrong delivery mechanism</span>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

